Cape Town - Arguments for the sentencing proceedings of ANC MPL Andile Lili who was convicted of inciting members of the Ses’khona People’s Rights Movement, to commit murder and common assault is expected to begin in March. The National Prosecuting Authority’s Eric Ntabazalila confirmed that the heads of arguments for sentencing must be submitted on February 10. The legal team together with the State are expected to conduct arguments in March before a decision is made on a sentencing date at the Bellville Magistrate’s Court. Ntabazalila explained: “Parties will argue on 2 and 3 March 2023 and the Magistrate will then decide on a date to hand down the sentence.” Lili also made headlines last year after he was charged with assault following an apparent incident involving a woman. Lili was convicted of attending an illegal gathering outside the courthouse in 2014 and 2015. He was also accused of leading members to the Cape Town International Airport Departure terminal where human waste was dumped. Lili is the founder oif the Ses’khona People’s Movement. He was suspended from the ANC following the incident of the service delivery protest using human waste. Weekend Argus